  Dublin is the capital and main port of the country. Here, you won't find any mind-blowing skyscrapers, world financial exchanges, and three-level road junctions on where the life of all modern capitals rushes. On the contrary, life in Dublin is measured and calm. Only a couple of times a year does the city explode during the bustling celebrations of St. Patrick and Bloom Days. Dublin is a city with a rich history that you can touch with your own hands. It is within the walls of the majestic St.
        Patrick's Cathedral, where Jonathan Swift created his Gulliver; in the library of the prestigious Trinity College, which houses the ancient manuscript known as the Book of Kells; in the Bell Tower of St. John's Church; in museums that tremblingly preserve the works of Velazquez, Picasso and Vermeer. But still, the Guinness Beer Museum (official name — "St. James's Gate Brewery") is the most visited attraction in Dublin (over 700,000 visitors a year). After getting acquainted with its most exciting exposition, you can go up to the observation deck of the museum, where you will be offered to taste the brewed beer and admire the panoramic view of the city.&nbsp;

<p>Galway is a port town that has grown from Fort Dún Bhun na Gaillimh on the west coast of the country. It has a festival temper with annual events dedicated to theatre, poetry, and ancient music. But the Oyster Festival and Galway Racing are especially famous. If this is your first time in town, start at Eyre Square; stroll through the scenic park of the National University of Ireland; look through the windows of Lynch's Castle, the one that invented the concept of lynching; take a photo at the Cathedral and St. Nicholas Collegiate Church and make sure you make a one-day trip to the Cliffs of Moher. The shadow turns the high cliffs almost black, the sun highlights the green hats of the meadows, and the white foam of the ocean blinds your eyes — it's truly an unforgettable experience!&nbsp;</p><p>In the heart of South Munster's most picturesque province, on the green hills of the rocky Atlantic coast, Limerick has grown to become a university city with a unique medieval charm. It is known for its colorful Gregorian architecture, massive fortifications, and an active nightlife. Local clubs and bars regularly host parties, stand-up comedies, and poetry evenings. The other places worth visiting include King John's Castle, on the banks of the River Shannon, the St. John's Cathedral, and the Hunt Museum, which displays a sketch by Picasso, an engraving by Paul Gauguin and a horse figure created by Leonardo da Vinci.</p><p>Cork is one of the largest cities in Ireland, located on the southwest coast. It is strict and pedantic during the day, while at night, it is bustling and noisy. Free and wild people would be interested in visiting numerous bars on St. Patrick's Street, and tourists with children would love Fota Wildlife Park. There are few prominent historical buildings in the city, which include the spectacular Neo-Gothic St. Mary's Cathedral and Saint Fin Barre's Cathedral. The neighborhood offers plenty of attractions for more than a weekend. First of all, we recommend visiting the ancient Blarney Castle. There are legends that if you kiss the Blarney Stone on one of the walls of the fort, you will be given an oratorical talent in the blink of an eye. It is unknown if it is true or not, but the stone has already earned fame as "the most unhygienic sight in Europe".</p><p>The city of Killarney in County Kerry began to earn money from tourism back in the XVIII century when the rest of Ireland was not even aware of this possibility. The infrastructure of the city is as comfortable as possible for tourists. There are plenty of attractions to see: the Neo-Gothic Cathedral of St. Mary, a Flemish altar in Muckross Abbey, hiking trails in the National Park, Torc Waterfall, and Ross Castle. Try the delicious seafood in the local restaurants and visit the music pubs, which are famous for their best folk songs performed all over the country. Then take a miniature journey along the Ring of Kerry, a scenic route along the coastline of the Iveragh Peninsula with some of the best views of the Atlantic coast.&nbsp;</p><p>In the middle of the XX century, the Red Vikings founded Waterford in southern Ireland. The fortress walls of the old town center, Reginald's Tower, Treasure Museum — every corner of the city keeps mysteries and legends about the harsh people who used to inhabit it. After a stroll through Waterford's paved streets and shady park alleys, be sure to check out T&amp;H Doolan's pub, which has been serving excellent beer and whiskey for over 300 years. But don't get carried away with alcohol as Waterford's neighborhood is also full of fantastic places. Be sure to visit the Sion Hill House &amp; Gardens, the authentic fishing village of Dunmore East, and the Blue Flag awarded beaches of Ardmore.</p>
